docs/ is the specification layer for `crates/steno` — three normative documents covering the pipeline architecture, the `.steno` source-format grammar, and the TypeScript-port rationale/precedent. Nothing here is compiled; these are the contracts an editor checks *before* touching `crates/steno/src`, and they explicitly cross-reference each other rather than duplicate: `steno-format.md` owns DSL grammar/parsing/count-merge rules, `pipeline.md` owns what happens to a parsed `Entry` afterward (pass order, module dependency direction, error taxonomy), and `porting-notes.md` records settled precedent for corpus/test edge cases that must not be "fixed" back toward TS parity.

The two technical docs share one seam: `%d`/`%[…%]`/`%(…)` template operators are *defined* syntactically in `steno-format.md` but their expansion-time semantics against a resolved count value belong to Pass A in `pipeline.md` — a change to repeat/computed-landing behavior must update both. `steno-format.md` also states a precedence rule that applies to the whole docs/ directory's relationship to code: where doc and implementation disagree, `crates/steno/src/{parse,stroke}` wins, not the doc. `porting-notes.md` pins two corpus states (`STKWR-FB`'s closed fence, `STKWR-LT` as a type-slot binding, not a template literal) that `pipeline.md`'s and `steno-format.md`'s described behaviors must remain compatible with — reverting either in `dict.steno` reopens closed test divergences.

`pipeline.md` is the map for restructuring pass boundaries or error types; `steno-format.md` is the map for grammar/directive changes; `porting-notes.md` is read-only precedent, consulted but not extended except when a new TS-vs-Rust divergence is deliberately introduced and resolved.

No intent.md exists for this directory.